otional from the physical. Legal expert Peter A. Alces contends that such theories are misguided—so misguided that they undermine law and, ultimately, human thriving. Building on the foundation outlined in his previous work, The Moral Conflict of Law and Neuroscience, Alces further investigates the implications for legal doctrine and practice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLaw and ethics. 0aLawxPhilosophy. 0aNeurosciences. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aneuroscience, morality, law, emotion, consequentialism, instrumentalism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079732940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226827490423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226827490/original  a978-3-11-079732-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles